fields.description: For once, the billing for this event is not hyperbole: " Four Tennis Legends/Two Epic Rivalries/One Smashing Event ."  John McEnroe, Ivan Lendl, Pete Sampras, and Andre Agassi  were all ranked the number one player in the world at least once in their careers and together hold almost 300 ATP-recognized titles. The showdown presents an eight-game pro set between McEnroe and Lendl and best-of-three matches between Sampras and Agassi. Sponsored by the European banking group BNP Paribas as part of their "Tennis Night in America," the meeting of four tennis legends is the perfect opportunity for those longing to hit the courts to see some high-powered action.
fields.title: Four Tennis Legends/Two Epic Events/One Smashing Evening

fields.description: Part of this bill duplicates a solid Bunker lineup from last summer. Marcel Dettman is a resident at Berlin's hedonistic Berghain, where his dark minimalism provides a throbbing aural dreamscape for dancing. Steffi plays at the affiliated Panoramabar, when not curating her limited-edition Dolly imprint. This time a British hard techno heavyweight joins them: Schooled as much by Coil and the Art of Noise as by Jeff Mills and Kraftwerk, Surgeon is a unique master of the genre, as he and his wifeÂ’s live audiovisual set should prove. With residents Spinoza and Eric Cloutier.
fields.title: Berghain and Panoramabar at the Bunker

fields.description:
Dir. Roman Polanski (1965).
Roman PolanskiÂ’s chic, creepy thriller (and first English language feature) was the ultimate in art-house grand guignol, featuring a nervy Chico Hamilton score,Â f/x swiped from Jean Cocteau, and one of the screenÂ’s most memorable rabbits, not to mention Catherine Deneuve, as convincing as she is fetching in the role of a psychotic manicurist.
fields.title: Repulsion

fields.description: When Anna Deavere Smith began adapting interviews concerning pressing issues for her one-woman stage verbatim documentaries, she really started something. This pack also turns their transcribed coverage into musicals: "Let Me Ascertain You" is the stage-documentary result of what they learned looking closely at the porn industry. The songs are by Michael Friedman, their most prolific (and overrated) tunesmith, and Jill Sobule. They swear there will also be prizes, but will there be a booby prize?
fields.title: The Civilians

fields.description: Dr. John (a/k/a Mac Rebennack) has been enjoying an artistic rebirth with a new band that allows his jazzbo-elder persona to blend with his spiritual gris-gris incarnation. Enjoy his bouncing Crescent City piano stylings and amazing voice--a greasy, grimy, gritty example of the Southern gothic sublime--during this two-night Mardi Gras run that also features one of the city's own better funk experimentalists, keyboard renegade Marco Benevento. With High & Mighty Brass Band.
fields.title: Dr. John & the Lower 911+Marco Benevento

fields.description: To paraphrase VarÃ¨se: The modern-day systems-oriented composer and blues guitarist refuses to die. The Issue Project Room presents a long-overdue overview of composer-multi-instrumentalist  Elliott Sharp  this weekend in the form of a two-night, two-venue 60th-birthday event. Tonight's benefit for the nonprofit arts org takes place in  IPR's new Â“jewel-boxÂ” theater in downtown Brooklyn. Sharp will premiere  Trinity  (with writer-narrator-host Steve Buscemi and filmmaker Jo Andres), the double-quartet IPR commission  Occam's Razor  and  Boreal . Tomorrow night's eight-hour this-is-your-life extravaganza takes place in IPR's current Can Factory space. Beginning at 5 p.m., it includes works featuring Sharp's Orchestra Carbon ( Flexagons ), his electronics-rocking Bootstrappers, a brain-scrambling eleven-guitar version of SyndaKit, excerpts from Sharp's Octal for eight-string guitarbass, and a screening of Bert Shapiro's E# documentary,  Doing the Don't.
fields.title: Elliott Sharp

fields.description:
Dir. Jafar Panahi (2003).
Jafar PanahiÂ’s deadpan dark comedy begins and ends with a real-time, fixed-camera jewelry-store robbery. As usual with this now-jailed Iranian director, Tehran is a character and there's a tremendous, impassive tragicomic performance by nonpro Hossain Emadeddin.
fields.title: Crimson Gold

fields.description: French provocateur Catherine Breillat has long tackled issues of gender and sexuality in her films such as  Fat Girl  and  The Last Mistress . So it's no wonder that what's lately been of interest to her are the fairy tales of Charles Perrault. In 2009, Breillat adapted his story  Bluebeard , about a husband who murders his disobedient wives, to explore the dangerous lessons learned by the story's young female readers. And now she presents  The Sleeping Beauty , which looks at mythologies told throughout history of little girls in danger. Tonight, the outspoken Breillat will discuss  The Sleeping Beauty  at a screening as a part of the 16th annual  Rendez-Vous With French Cinema  series, presented by Unifrance. You can also catch the filmmaker on Monday at IFC (323 Sixth Avenue) for a screening and discussion about Elia Kazan's very naughty  Baby Doll , which concerns a husband whose sultry child bride won't allow him to touch her. We're sure she'll have plenty to say about that.
fields.title: Rendez-Vous With French Cinema

fields.description:
Dir. Bertrand Tavernier (1992).
A rambling exercise in nouveau grit, Bertrand TavernierÂ’s policier is an engagingly jaunty and discursive drama of life on the Parisian narco beat. Confounding genre expectations, the film has insouciance but no catharsis.
fields.title: L.627

fields.description: In all the years that  Bridget Everett  has been commanding cabaret stages by stripping down to her undies and singing raunchy love songs accompanied by little more than a bottle of Chardonnay, her mother has never come to Manhattan to see her perform. Imagine that. But everything is about to change when EverettÂ’s mom flies in from the other Manhattanâ€”Kansasâ€”to check out tonight's show. Everett will be dedicating some new covers to her mom, like Adina Howard's "Freak Like Me" and Prince's "How Come U DonÂ’t Call Me Anymore." Naturally, sheÂ’s not sure how Mom will take it. "I told her I was nervous that she was coming," says Everett, "and she said, 'You know I think youÂ’re perfect just the way you are.' So I'm gonna test her."
fields.title: Bridget Everett

fields.description: Downtown Records flaunts their roster with a line-up that you'd normally have to wait for CMJ to see--and tonight, you'll get it for less than a theater or arena show. The only problem is that you'll be worn out by the end of the evening, unless you want to miss an ace turntablist/fashion plate (A-Trak), the most self-conscious bar band since Hold Steady (Art Brut), a genre-defying indie trio (White Denim), an ex-model turned tense rocker (Lissie Trullie), or a fun-time Japanese girl group (the Suzan).
fields.title: 'Downtown Music Festival Presents A-Trak+Art Brut+White Denim'
"An Evening with Nao Bustamante: Melted, Plotting Out a Cross-Genre Narrative"

fields.description: Dir. Alice Guy BlachÃ© (1896).
fields.title: GodÂ’s Offices

fields.description: Author Charles King's colorful account of the transformation of one of EuropeÂ‘s foremost Jewish cities is told through the stories of its geniuses and villains.
fields.title: Lecture - Odessa: Genius And Death In A City Of Dreams

fields.description: Just as the Metropolitan Museum of Art is paying tribute to fashionable women from the past and present, the Museum of Modern Art is also celebrating those with XX chromosomes with  Pictures by Women: A History of Modern Photography . The exhibition, featuring more than 200 works by 120 artists, reveals the essence of womanhood with works by Diane Arbus, Tina Modotti, Cindy Sherman, and Carrie Mae Weems, as well as pictures, collages, videos, and photography-based installations by Yoko Ono, Lorna Simpson, and Kiki Smith. The images depict everything from domestic life (American photographer Gertrude KÃ¤sebierÂ’s 1899 elegant black-and-white photograph  Blessed Art Thou Among Women  of a young girl in a school uniform alongside her mother in a nightgown) to domestic violence (Nan GoldinÂ’s Nan  One Month After Being Battered , a 1984 self-portrait of her bruised and bloodied face after her boyfriend beat her up)Â—all powerful examples of the female experience.
fields.title: Pictures by Women: A History of Modern Photography

fields.description: The Beastie Boys, Run-DMC, Sonic YouthÂ—if you missed living in the city in the Â’80s and Â’90s (or were too young to apprecaite it),  Looking at Music 3.0  takes you back to New YorkÂ’s glory days, when art thrived on city walls, underground clubs, and alternative space. This show, the third in a series that explores the influence of music on contemporary art practices, features about 70 pieces that center around the birth of Â“remix cultureÂ” and the activism that arose in response to the AIDS crisis, the cityÂ’s financial problems, and the rampant drug use destroying neighborhoods. Artists included are Public Enemy, Kathleen Hanna and Le Tigre, Keith Haring, Christian Marclay, Lee Quinones, and Miranda July, who founded Â“Joanie 4 Jackie,Â” a video chain letter.
fields.title: Looking at Music 3.0

fields.description: It's been a while since we last got to venue-hop among downtown black-boxes for a theater festival, so Frigid is back to once again fill the void left by those departed warm-weather mega-fests. See how many of the 30 shows you can catch in 12 days. It's for a good cause: 100 percent of box-office proceeds go to the artists who created the shows (that doesn't usually happen at New York festivals). Some highlights on the largely solo-show roster are  Hi, How Can I Help You? , Scout Durwood's one-woman musical comedy about the sex-industry;  My Pal Izzy , Melanie Gall's biographical take on Irving Berlin, using some of his lesser-known tunes; and  ONEymoon , Christel Bartelse's tale about a woman who marries herself.
fields.title: Frigid Festival

fields.description: Traveling the world for the fashion magazine  W ,  Philip-Lorca DiCorcia  has photographed subjects ranging from exotic dancers in Havana to Marc Jacobs in his bedroom in Paris. For the first time ever in his 30-year career, the American photographer and reinventor of street photography will exhibit 11 of his fashion portfolios that he and  W  magazine's long-time creative director, Dennis Freedman (who is now the creative director at Barneys), worked on together. Featuring locations such as a cockfighting ring in Bangkok and a museum in Cairo, the images will transport you to another world.
fields.title: Philip-Lorca DiCorcia
Subject of the Question+Luster+Drum the Jaguar

fields.description: Dir. Robert Kramer (1985).
fields.title: Our Nazi

fields.description: Kanye West is no stranger to controversyâ€”so for his new album cover, he wanted a like-minded artist to be as out there as he is. Naturally, he approached artist  George Condo . The rapper wanted Condo, who once worked as a printer for Andy Warhol, to create an album cover that would get Â“banned.Â” However, the cover for WestÂ’s  My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy , featuring a trippy brightly colored image of a devilish monkey screwing a naked female monster with wings and a tail, never did get bannedâ€”in fact, even Wal-Mart was excited to sell it.  Mental States , CondoÂ’s first major U.S. survey, is just as out there, with more than 80 paintings and sculptures from the past 28 years of the artistÂ’s career. The exhibition, divided on two floors and separated in chapter form, details the artistÂ’s unique adaptation of Old Master paintings and has its own share of female monsters and strange monkey people suitable for rock stars and us weirdly normal folk.
fields.title: George Condo

fields.description: In 1974, American sculptor artist  Lynda Benglis  posed for  Artforum  wearing nothing but sunglasses and a giant latex dildo. This was her attempt to say, in so many words, that the art world isnÂ’t a manÂ’s world. Nearly four decades later, we are still taking notice of her brilliant work as the New Museum presents her first major retrospective in more than 20 years. The show includes her infamous poured latex pieces from the Â’60s and Â’70s, early bronze casts, wax reliefs, videos, BenglisÂ’s largest pour sculpture at almost 40 feet in length titled Â“Contraband,Â” which was first seen at the Whitney, and Â“Phantom,Â” a polyurethane installation consisting of five monumental sculptures that glow in the dark. WeÂ’ll be wearing shades, too.
fields.title: Lynda Benglis

fields.description: "It will be funny a thousand years from now," Woody Allen has said about the work of silent-film pioneer Charlie Chaplin. Indeed, you don't need to understand the language to know when a pratfall is funny.  Silent Clowns  is a new film series of screenings and discussions that explores how Chaplin's physical comedy influenced future comedians in film. It starts tonight with  Modern Times , Chaplin's 1936 Depression-era masterpiece starring the Little Tramp as a factory worker driven crazy by his monotonous work on the assembly line. After the screening, Saul Austerlitz, author of  Another Fine Mess , will discuss Chaplin's work. Upcoming movies in the series are Jerry Lewis's  The Bellboy  (March 29), Peter Sellers's  The Party  (April 7), and Woody Allen's  Zelig  (May 3).
fields.title: Silent Clowns

fields.description: Taking a rare break from making  Are We There Yet?  sequels and TV episodes, family actor Ice Cube has returned to his first love: gangsta rap. After all so many years of having other careers in tandem with hip-hop, he has always comes back swinging. His last album, 2010's middling  I Am the West , showed a lot of promise, though, mostly thanks to production from Sir Jinx--the man partly responsible for the sound on Cube's early '90s solo albums. "Life in California" in which he takes potshots at Jay-Z and Alicia Keys' ubiquitous "Empire State of Mind." Once a fighter, always a fighter.
fields.title: Ice Cube

fields.description: Jesse Eisenberg did a stellar job portraying the nerdy Facebook creator Mark Zuckerberg in  Social Network , perhaps because he, too, is shy and awkward. Also like Zuckerberg, Eisenberg is very charitable. Tonight, he'll give a reading along with actress Lili Taylor at Now Showing, the Alliance for Young Artists & Writers's fundraiser for creative scholarships. The night of lit, music, and art also includes a silent auction and the sounds of Rasputina, Max Vernon, and DJ Gilles Wasserman. We're going simply to see if Eisenberg will showcase some more of that charming pizzazz we saw on  Saturday Night Live .
fields.title: Now Showing

fields.description:
You can get into all sorts of fistfights and parlor games about who's the most innovative jazz pianist around these days: Jason Moran or this New York mainstay. Moran's more trad-bound--and, not
coincidentally, more feted--but despite Shipp's avant-garde roots, his latest disc includes his takes on "Fly Me to the Moon" and "Take the A Train," neither of which would upset anyone down the street at Blue Note. His playing is luxurious no matter what style he plumbs, and he's still got a lot to prove at 50 years young. With Weasel Walter/Mary Halvorson/Peter Evans Trio.
fields.title: 'Thirsty Ear Presents an Evening of Trio Treats with Matthew Shipp Trio'

fields.description: This new L.A. combo finds well-traveled indie-scene drummer Barbara Gruska (who's played with Jenny Lewis and the Watson Twins) doing sunshiney, soul-infused folk-pop with her younger brother Ethan. Their handsome, self-titled debut is due out in April, and they'll follow this small-room gig by opening for Grace Potter & the Nocturnals at Irving Plaza later this week. With Sneaky Legend, Noah Chernin, and Go Back to the Zoo.
fields.title: The Belle Brigade

fields.description: It has been a decade since snotty pop-punk marionettes Good Charlotte first ruled (and arguably killed) MTV. Somehow, despite emo rendering pop-punk commercially obsolete, they've managed to maintain their traction and most of their original lineup, even scoring a platinum single in 2007. Now, as most of their pop-punk peers seem to have fallen by the wayside--be it taking up writing Broadway musicals or hosting shows on Fuse--Good Charlotte are still trying to live out their "Lifestyles of the Rich and Famous." Their future is in your hands. With Forever the Sickest Kids and This Century.
fields.title: Good Charlotte

fields.description: After a year of calypso gold, Montreal solo artist Grimes will usher in 2011's newest influence: lo-fi Enya. Her soaring monosyllabic utterings are matched by a dreamy palette of Eastern influences and glitchy beats--hearts are captured with one bounce of her token Troll-hair updo. Backups Doldrums (Toronto art rock), Megafortress (one man desert-drone), and Toby Aronson (Vermont acoustics) finish off a night at Glasslands that should be Crystal Castles for the unfamiliar. With Alaskas.
fields.title: Grimes+Doldrums

fields.description:
Dir. Joseph von Sternberg (1930).
The great cine-aestheteÂ’s first talkie (and only German film) is as stodgy as it is sleazy, as static as it is iconic, in detailing the S&M affair between a meaty, young Marlene Dietrich and a decrepit, old Emil Jannings.
fields.title: The Blue Angel

fields.description:
Dir. C. Scott Willis (2010).
This documentary portrait of the artist, the photographer Francesca Woodman who committed suicide in 1981 at age 22, is also haunting study in family dynamicsÂ—the film leaves the impression that FrancescaÂ’s parents,Â  a strong-willed ceramicist and a stubbornly unfashionable abstract painter, regard their doomed genius child as their greatest work of art.
fields.title: The Woodmans

fields.description: No longer content to provide the backing music to the Masturbating Bear (the Conan O'Brien character--not his boss, the Boss), drummer Max Weinberg quit late-night TV last year to continue playing with the E Street band and start the ensemble he's leading tonight, the Max Weinberg Big Band. What began as an one-off in December--when the 12-piece group played the music of Count Basie and Buddy Rich--has led to a Monday residency at the Hiro Ballroom beginning tonight. Were that not enough, curious fans can also ask for a "Mighty Max cocktail."
fields.title: Max Weinberg Big Band

fields.description:
Dir. Elia Kazan (1956).
Tennessee Williams concocted this mad Actors Studio farce, Kazan's only comedy, in which a Mississippi child bride who refuses to allow her glad-handing husband to touch her, gets seduced (maybe) by his hated, ultra-ethnic rival. New York archbishop Francis Cardinal Spellman warned that seeing the movie was in itself a sin.
fields.title: Baby Doll

fields.description: Battles was only the beginning. After leaving the New York post-rock collective, composer/singer/guitarist  Tyondai Braxton  vowed to focus on his experimental solo work, and tonight he'll get a ringing endorsement from some like-minded conjurors, the Wordless Music Orchestra. His dense symphonics have been well represented in his inquisitive voice and steeped-pedal strings, but the additional creative ensemble will broach new territory in their selections from his 2009 Warp disc  Central Market  and new compositions. Perhaps he has finally set the  Onion  article devoted to him (see Â“Temp Hides Fun, Fulfilling Life From Rest of OfficeÂ” discussing one Â“Ty BraxtonÂ”) into elegant quatrains. Part of the Tully Scope Festival.
fields.title: Tyondai Braxton

fields.description: Jeff Mills is one of techno's living legends: He co-founded Underground Resistance, dominated Detroit underground radio as the Wizard, created his own future-theorist vocabulary, released records on Berlin's Tresor and served as a Limelight resident. He's taken some forays away from his punishing minimalistic sound by collaborating with the Montpellier Philharmonic Orchestra, writing his own soundtrack for Metropolis, and experimenting with site-specific work, but tonight should find him at his classic best: speed-mixing record after record with an aggressive but sure hand. With residents Sleepy & Boo.
fields.title: Basic NYC Presents Jeff Mills

fields.description: According to humorist P.G. Wodehouse, "Alcohol is a misunderstood vitamin," and it seems like cook-off professionals Theo Peck and Nick Suarez would agree, as their competition, the  Brooklyn Booze Experiment , at the Bell House, is where amateur chefs will show off their best booze-inspired dishes. From the richest bourbon sauces and braised meats to the most indulgent desserts topped with alcoholic whipped creams, you're invited to sample each intoxicating Â“experimentÂ” and select the winner, along with expert judges. You can even feel good about blowing your beer money on the event: A portion of ticket sales will help support ovarian cancer research. Wine and dine away!
fields.title: Brooklyn Booze Experiment

fields.description: An indie-country semi-supergroup with members of Dawes, Deer Tick, and Delta Spirit, Middle Brother are like the Crosby Stills & Nash of the Bonnaroo set. (Unless that's what Monsters of Folk were?) Tonight, they'll play after warm-up sets by Dawes and Deer Tick, which means some kind of all-hands jam seems destined.
fields.title: Middle Brother+Dawes+Deer Tick

fields.description: Simpatico is the fruit of dumb luck, hard work, or a combination of the two. Happily, the virtuoso fiddler and insightful guitarist have had it from the get-go; their art is a marvel of shared dynamics that milks all the poignancy from the jigs, reels, and airs comprising their Celtic songbook. Their gentility coincides with a stealthy splash of aggression, and it makes pieces such as "The Cat in the Corner" and "Green Gowned Lass" both seductive and beguiling.
fields.title: Martin Hayes & Dennis Cahill

fields.description:
Dir. Buster Keaton & Clyde Bruckman (1926).
At once archaic in its pastoral view of America and modern in its vision of the mechanical technology, KeatonÂ’s Civil War comedy is arguably the most beautiful of his featuresÂ—not least in its amazingly orchestrated locomotive gags.
fields.title: The General

fields.description: Chicago's Smith Westerns pushed their way into the indie spotlight with a scraggly, jutting-chin debut for HoZac Records that reveled in its youthful bravado like a teenage motorcycle gang with a death wish. Having moved up to Fat Possum and a fatter production budget for the recent  Dye It Blonde , they now have the means to make the girls cream over their Millennial vigor and glitter rock reduxes. They're like a cleaner cut Black Lips who'd rather kiss your mouth than spit in each other's. Expect more from these dudes. With Unknown Mortal Orchestra and Computer Magic.
fields.title: Smith Westerns

fields.description: Folksy, surreal guitarist Ben Chasny is an avant-garde talent who often pads his records with odd drones and pauses. In concert, he'll probably hover around his more focused riff cycles--they're not quite as seductively meditative but are a wise move that will avoid the sort of self-indulgent, six-string fingerpainting that can burden his albums.
fields.title: Six Organs of Admittance

fields.description: Hidden Recordings boss Deepak Sharma celebrates his and Dieter Krause's new release,  Wolkenreise . Melodic and laidback, their latest slice of Balearic soul features a slew of remixes by artists including John Tejada and DJ Qu, and the latter joins Sharma tonight. With his cohorts on Underground Quality, DJ Qu helped make NY-area house a vital force again; his warm, straightforward sets never disappoint. With Domingo Cava.
fields.title: Wolkenreise Release Party-Hidden Records

fields.description: We know we're not the only ones who have fantasized about faking our own death and going undercover to the funeral just to see what people would say about us. Todd Zuniga certainly thinks about it. The co-creator of Literary Death Match (we're seeing a pattern here) asked 40 writers, filmmakers, musicians, and others to write their own obituaries for the exhibition  Let It End Like This . The results, contributed by artists from Moby and Tao Lin to Susan Orlean and Eugene Mirman, range from funny to, well, morbid. Other participants include Aaron Garretson, Sam Lipsyte, Sarah McNally, Dinaw Mengestu, James J. Williams III, and Evie Wylde.
fields.title: Let It End Like This

fields.description: From the vast Andy Warhol film repertoire, it was his silent black-and-white films from the mid-Â’60s that best conveyed his raw talent and brilliant eye for subtlety. TodayÂ’s opening of Andy Warhol: Motion Pictures includes his  Screen Tests  (featuring portraits of Lou Reed, Allen Ginsberg, Salvador DalÃ­, Susan Sontag, and Edie Sedgwick), which will be shown on the gallery walls within frames, as well as his early silent black-and-white films (such as  Sleep, Eat, Blow Job , and  Kiss ). A selection of these films are being seen in a way that Warhol had always intended them to be seenÂ—slower, the way silent films were viewed from the 1890s through the 1920s. Although they were originally shot at sound-film speed (24 frames per second), for this exhibition, the films have been transferred from 16mm film to DVD at the speed of 16 frames per second.
fields.title: Andy Warhol: Motion Pictures

fields.description: You wanted a hit? Well,  The People's Key  is  Bright Eyes ' most straightforward, nose-to-grindstone rock album yet, and just in time to be a rollicking swan song, as scarily prolific mastermind Conor Oberst has maintained it will be the last for the group (Oberst, Mike Mogis, and Nathaniel Walcot). (He hasn't said much to corroborate it lately, though; all theories welcome, with bonus points for Winona conspiracies.) The album's pretty Hitler-obsessed, but even that bleak cloud can't numb the gorgeous emotional resonance of wafting psychedelia number Â“Haile SelassieÂ” and triumphant banner-waver Â“Jejune Stars.Â” Even if you've disparaged emo-rock before, don't close the door without opening this window first.
fields.title: Bright Eyes

fields.description: Â“I didn't want to be a fashion designer at all,Â” Dame Vivienne Westwood told  The New York Times . Â“I did it to help my boyfriend.Â” Her boyfriend was, of course, Malcolm McLaren, manager of the Sex Pistols. Together, they invented the radical punk style of the '70sÂ—safety pins, ripped T-shirts, spiked dog collars around the neck. How Westwood went from the streets to the high-fashion runways is the focus of the new exhibit at FIT titled  Vivienne Westwood 1980Â–89 . The collection tracks her transition from her 1981 unisex pirate-themed collection to creating styles that were more feminine and structured, gaining her a wider audience and more attention from the mainstream press. The exhibition features highlights from her collections (including her iconic Â“Rocking HorseÂ” boots), footage from the runway shows, photographs from magazines, and video interviews with Westwood.
fields.title: Vivienne Westwood 1980Â–89

fields.description: Technologies old and new clamor and collide in the world premiere of Gosfield's  Daughters of the Industrial Revolution , a concert-length work for acoustic and electric ensembles in ideological opposition. Gosfield has a startling knack for transforming the sounds of science and technology into inventive music: this work contrasts modern electronics with the sounds of the junkyards and sweatshops her immigrant grandparents experienced on the Lower East Side. Stephen Gosling will also perform "Lightning Slingers and Dead Ringers," a work for piano and sampler.
fields.title: Annie Gosfield

fields.description: Though I was born too late to enjoy an '80s prom myself, I may once have actively requested Bon Jovi's "You Give Love a Bad Name" at a junior high semiformal. Conversely, this interactive show aims to give nostalgia musicals a good name when it invites audiences to drink, dance, and vote for prom king and queen. SOLOSKI.
fields.title: The Awesome '80s Prom

fields.description: If you saw Lena Dunham's film  Tiny Furniture , you're familiar with the work of her mother,  Laurie Simmons , who starred in the film, more or less as herself, photographing tiny figurines in her Tribeca home just as she does in real life. For her new solo show,  The Love Doll: Days 1Â–30 , Simmons ordered two lifelike Â“love dollsÂ” from a factory in Japan and posed them lounging around her estate in ConnecticutÂ—playing naked with a dog, climbing a wall, and diving into a swimming pool. But perhaps the oddest photo of all is the one of an Asian doll packed inside a cardboard box, waiting for her owner to greet her.
fields.title: The Love Doll: Days 1Â–30

fields.description:
Catherine Breillat, 2010) Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  Walter Reade 3/4, 8
Catherine BreillatÂ’s latest fractured fairytale is less primal and more convoluted than her version of BluebeardÂ—tricked out with dreams, doubles, and interpolations from Hans Christian AndersenÂ—but equally perverse in its saga of female actualization.
fields.title: The Sleeping Beauty

fields.description:
Dir. Joe May (1929).
A dumb but honest police officer (Gustav FrÃ¶hlich, the young hero of Metropolis) is led astray by a larcenous shady lady (sultry flapper Betty Amann) in this echt Weimar late silent; indeed heÂ’s literally overpowered by the force of her sex appeal.
fields.title: Asphalt

fields.description:
Dir. Alain Resnais (1968).
Never released in the US and rarely screened, Alain ResnaisÂ’s 1968 time-travel fantasy is both goofy and poeticÂ—a sensationally well-edited succession of flashbacks. As a sci-fi love story it recalls Chris MarkerÂ’s  La Jetee  and anticipates Steven SoderberghÂ’s  Solaris  remake.
fields.title: Je tÂ’aime, je tÂ’aime

fields.description: The Violets' men's track team is enjoying a record-setting season, and a strong performance can be expected when they host the  Division III Men's Track and Field Championships . Watch for Daniel McKinney, who set a school record in the 200-meter dash on February 19, and freshman Gilson Cortes, whose record McKinney broke. Matt Turlip put in a record-setting performance on the mile (4:06:65) at the Valentine's Invitational, the best posting by an NYU student since the school joined Division III in 1982 and placing him seventh-best Division III. Also, in the 3000-meter, Andrew Zitek and Sebastian Schwelm rank in the top 10 in NYU's Div III history. Bonus: The Armory Track and Field Center is located in the old Fort Washington Armory, a gorgeous Classical Revival building that is state-of-the-art for track and field events. It's also home to the National Track and Field Hall of Fame, which alone is worth the trip uptown.
fields.title: Division III Men's Track and Field Championships

fields.description: Move over, Barnum and BaileyÂ—there's a new circus in town. The Australian performance company  Circa  melds choreography and acrobatics andÂ—unlike Cirque du SoleilÂ—opts for a stripped-down aesthetic, wowing audiences around the globe in prestigious venues such as the Sydney Opera House, Dublin Theatre Festival, and the Barbican in London. Set to a soundtrack that includes Sigur RÃ³s, Leonard Cohen, and Jacquel Brel, its self-titled New York debut features grueling, emotionally charged feats of physical capability. Multi-skilled performers often grimace as they work through intricate, risky routines in which timing and accuracy are everything (for instance, when a woman in red stilettos walks all over a man's body, there's little room for error). It's no surprise that many performers leave visibly battered and bruised.
fields.title: Circa

fields.description: Ahmadinejad would likely not approve. With its  Iranian Theater Festival , the Brick Theater unfurls a Persian carpet of conversation and performance works, many of them highly experimental, which explore Iranian history and identity. As theater has existed in Iran since 1000 B.C., theyÂ’ll have quite a lot to draw upon. The festival includes plays in English and Persian on subjects such as Â“murders, suicides, and rabbitsÂ”; Â“how hard it is to keep a chador onÂ”; HitlerÂ’s doppelgÃ¤nger; and the Iran/Iraq War as performed by marionettes. Additional events include an Iranian New YearÂ’s party, live Skype chats with Iranian citizens, and a panel on controversial visionary director Reza Abdoh staffed with several of his collaborators, including Juliana Francis-Kelly and Tony Torn.
fields.title: Iranian Theatre Festival

fields.description: The ultra-poised pianist celebrates a radiant new solo disc by playing in an array of configurations, minus one: solo. The brass and reeds added to his trio will make for a fetching fivesome, but his duos may best illustrate the intimacy that's long marked Hersch's work. Kate McGarry's vocals and Julian Lage's guitar should offer fanciful exchanges, and his shared air space with saxophonist Joshua Redman already has local zealots anxious to absorb the action.
fields.title: Fred Hersch Duos & Trios Plus 2

fields.description: In 1967, Surgeon General William Stewart announced, Â“ItÂ’s time to close the book on infectious disease.Â” That book still remains open, but in the futuristic world that closes Adam RappÂ’s new play cycle,  The Hallway Trilogy , sickness has indeed been exterminated, except in an East Side tenement museum in which cash-strapped volunteers are infected with antiquated illnesses to delight the public. Each of RappÂ’s new plays take place in that same tenement. The first, set in 1953 concerns an actress; the second, situated in the present, follows a squabbling couple; and the third, which occurs 50 years hence, is the museum piece. Directors Rapp, Daniel Aukin, Trip Cullman, and a cast of downtown luminaries offer these infectious evenings.
fields.title: The Hallway Trilogy

fields.description: Start planning what youÂ’ll smuggle in to this show by the Flying Karamazov Brothers: a bowling ball, a kitten, a bowl of Jell-O. If you bring it, they will juggle it. This loopy circus show, which enjoyed a successful run earlier this year, combines circus arts, comedy, music, dance, and ample absurdity.
fields.title: 4Play

fields.description: If you've missed out on the oodles of art-show openings this year, or have been out of the art-world loop, don't fretÂ—the 13th annual  Armory Show , which started Thursday, is your one-two punch for all things art. Once again, the Armory Show presents Â“Armory Arts Week,Â” a series of public programming taking place in a different neighborhood each night. The events include special receptions, open studios, art tours, museum discounts, performances, panels, artist discussions, and parties. Of course the big draw is the Armory Show itself, which features the most important artworks of the 20th and 21st centuries from the world's leading galleries. Another big highlight will be the show's focus on Latin American art, featuring galleries from Argentina, Brazil, Chile, Colombia, Mexico, Peru, and Venezuela. And don't forget to stop by Volta NY, the Armory Show's sister fair at 7W (7 West 34th Street), for a collection of edgy solo projects.
fields.title: Armory Show

fields.description: The Bad Plus pianist treats his extracurricular activities with a refreshing informality. When he blows through jazz nuggets such as "Good Bait" or "Little Melonae," he likes to slap 'em around a bit. The deconstruction comes naturally--Iverson and associates always swing. From Billy Hart to Tootie Heath, he's been test-driving elder drummers of late, so his reconnection with superhero Motian should be sweet.
fields.title: Ethan Iverson, Larry Grenadier & Paul Motian

fields.description: Since making her mark on the scene with  Frozen Â—a knockout play about a child killer, his psychiatrist, and the mother of one of his victimsÂ—Bryony Lavery has taken some punches. In the midst of the play's triumph, she was hit with accusations of plagiarism. A lesser woman and writer might have stayed down, but Lavery came back swinging, issuing an apology and going on to write a series of formal and thematically challenging plays, often in the company of stimulating collaborators. The latest,  Beautiful Burnout , produced by the National Theatre of Scotland, is no exception. Partnering with Steven Hoggett, who did the extraordinary choreography for  Black Watch , she has created a battering, thumping, and striking play about the habituÃ©s of a Glasgow boxing gym. Previews begin tonight, opens
fields.title: Beautiful Burnout

fields.description: Â“I don't play accurately,Â” says a character in Oscar WildeÂ’s famed farce, Â“any one can play accurately, but I play with wonderful expression.Â” LetÂ’s hope that holds true for actor Brian Bedford, who will not only direct RoundaboutÂ’s revival, but also assume the doughty role of Lady Bracknell.
fields.title: The Importance of Being Earnest

fields.description: He won a Tony in 2009 for starring as the mentally disturbed ruler in  Exit the King . Now Geoffrey Rush stars as another neurotic in  The Diary of a Madman , based on one of Nikolai GogolÂ’s greatest short stories about a civil servant named Poprischin who is slowly being driven insane by the repressive bureaucratic system he slaves under in St. Petersburg. Rush, who originally played the lead in Australian director Neil ArmfieldÂ’s 1989 production, reprised his role in December at the Belvoir St. Theatre in Sydney to rave reviews and, lucky us, itÂ’s now here at BAM. Armfield, who also directed  Exit the King , reunites with Rush to stage the revival. Note that there is no Sunday, February 27, performance because, you know, a very important speech therapist has a special date at the Oscars.
fields.title: The Diary of a Madman

fields.description: Instead of the  Diary of a Young Girl , playwright Rinne Groff offers a play that might be titled  The Memoirs of a Middle-Aged Man . In  Compulsion , her ingenious mingling of historical fact and fiction centers on a writer named Sid Silver (based on the real-life figure Meyer Levin). Fixated on Anne FrankÂ’s diary, Silver spends much of his life in the U.S. and Israel struggling to promote the girlÂ’s story and adapt it to the stageÂ—for reasons that may seem less altruistic than they first appear. Mandy Patinkin and Hannah Cabell, as Silver and his wife, reprise their roles from the New Haven debut, and Oskar Eustis again directs this half-invented chronicle. Will it obsess audiences?
fields.title: Compulsion

fields.description: At the Passover seder, one asks, Â“Why is this night different from all other nights?Â” That wonÂ’t be difficult to answer at Matthew LopezÂ’s singular play, staged by MTC. BarrieÂ’s classic story Peter and the Starcatcher. Adapted from the book by Ridley Pearson and Dave Barry, the story takes you on an adventure with Peter Pan and his wily gang of orphans as they gather something called Â“starstuff.Â” Though Disney is known for its grand musical productions, this is the first time the company is doing a stripped-down play with little scenery and a dozen actors playing roughly 50 characters. After all, bigger does not always mean better (ahem,  Spider-Man ).
fields.title: Peter and the Starcatcher

The lecture looks at the step-by-step making of Guernica, taking advantage of the set of photographs of the work in progress taken by Dora Maar. Clark was a professor of modern art at the University of California, Berkeley from 1988 Â– 2010. His books include The Painting of Modern Life: Paris in the Art of Manet and His Followers (Princeton University Press, 1985), The Sight of Death: An Experiment in Art Writing (Yale University Press, 2006) and the forthcoming Picasso and Truth: From Cubism to Guernica. On their recordings, and every Tuesday at BarbÃ¨s, the 10-person brass ensemble pins Gypsy melodies against the sort of jazzy r&b horn collages you hear in movies adapted from Elmore Leonard books. The best part, though, is how they interact with their audience at their concerts, sometimes breaking the fourth wall, and really making each word in their nameÂ—especially the lastÂ—pull its weight.

In his newest show,  Unearth , Pandian investigates the remnants of the Native American City of Cahokia (in Illinois). The result is his own ancient-like treasure in which he has constructed five massive pillars made of rammed earth with layers of other materials, including shells and strips of 16mm film, embedded like strata in order to show Â“the relationship between ancient and modern cultures and the ways in which contemporary societies understand and treat the monuments of societies past.Â”

fields.description: Between "Lust for Life" 's revival as a Carnival Cruise jingle and the agonizing walk past the John Varvatos store where CBGB's used to be, it's no secret that punk-rock culture has seen some ugly lows. Green Day's Broadway musical  American Idiot , however, may just carve out a mosh pit for itself among these contenders. Tony-winning director Michael Mayer ( Spring Awakening ) is behind this venture, which features songs from the  American Idiot  and  21st Century Breakdown  albums. The show premiered at the Berkeley Rep and earned a range of decent to glowing reviews. From what we can tell, expect lots of heavily stylized thrashing and sets that make for a candy-colored faux-boho vibe not wholly unlike  Rent . John Gallagher Jr., who won a Tony for his role in  Spring Awakening , stars as the jaded suburbanite slacker Johnny.

A Â“Learn the RopesÂ” class for beginners costs $60 and includes two-day passes and rental gear. But perhaps most attractive to the skinny-jeans crowd (and youÂ’ll see a lot of them here on the weekends) is the dance-club-volume stereo system that cranks out rock while you get in shape.

fields.description: They say crying is good for you; if thatÂ’s true,  Laurel Nakadate  is doing just dandy. One photographic portion of  Only the Lonely  chronicles the artist before, during, and after weeping every day for a year. Being that this is NakadateÂ’s first large-scale museum exhibition, weÂ’re guessing those are tears of joy. If photographs of private moments of sadness arenÂ’t voyeuristic enough, check out what else is on view: videos from the past decade, in which the artist danced, posed, or played dead in the homes of anonymous men; and recent photos exploring the adolescent female body, for which Nakadate entered young womenÂ’s bedrooms while they were sleeping, woke them, and told them to strip to their underwear.

fields.description: There have been countless times that weÂ’ve strolled through MOMA, come upon an arousing piece, and dug in our bag looking for a pen to make a note for later inspiration. But what if you could create your own artwork inspired by the eclectic ambience of the museum right there and then? The new  Material Lab  allows you to do that, and, even better, you donÂ’t have to bring your entire collection of scraps, paints, pencils, Crayons, glue sticks, or anythingÂ—they provide all the supplies! The interactive space also includes a digital painting program, so you can take your art on-the-go, leave it to inspire others, or start your own gallery in your living room. The possibilities are endless.
fields.title: Material Lab

fields.description: And you thought gaming on your big flat-screen TV was fun? Beijing-based artist Feng Mengbo invites viewers to pick up a wireless controller and get into the action with his interactive video-game installation  Long March: Restart 2008 . Blending propaganda from Communist China with imagery from classic games such as  Street Fighter II  and  Super Mario Bros. , Mengbo has created a fully functioning video game in eight large-scale projections that requires you to actually walk along with the hero, a Red Army soldier, as he faces down the enemy in dangerous territory.
fields.title: Long March: Restart 2008

fields.description: A film, a comic, other assorted media accoutrements:  Out of Our Minds , Melissa Auf der Maur's second and long-time-coming 2010 solo album, came with everything but a rebate for Shake Weights. An ambitious if largely hook-free alchemy of '90s alt posturing, Viking barbarism, and Danzig guest shots, the album nevertheless established former Hole bassist "MAdM" (natch) as a strong artist for a new age of dream metal nerds. She is your queen. Note that animal sacrifices are prohibited at Highline Ballroom. With the Shining Twins and Leah Siegel.
fields.title: Melissa Auf der Maur

fields.description: Psychedelia and neo-folk are in multicultural array tonight, and their tension is universal: These artists all reside in quiet singer-songwriter moments but have the intensity of far more scabrous acts. MaineÂ’s  Arborea  chirp coyly with woodsy, autumnal banjo plucking, joined tonight by Helena Espvall of Espers on cello. Espvall, a Swedish multi-instrumentalist, will also perform a solo set of free improv, hopefully also cherry-picking from her two albums of native folk songs with Tokyo musician Masaki Batoh. Local player Matteah Baim, formerly of hard rock outfit Metallic Falcons, rounds out the set with her nuanced, assertive solo fare.

fields.description: We're just gonna say it:  Tennis  beats Hockey. The Denver husband-and-wife duo, Patrick Riley and Alaina Moor, are romantic souls, having recently completed an eight-month sailing journey along the Atlantic coastline. The delectably expansive, thoughtfully versed folk of January's  Cape Dory  (named after, yes, a type o' yacht) benefits from their shared wanderlust; the title track alone is something Daniel Johnston would tip his cap to. With La Ser anad Holiday Shores.
fields.title: Tennis

fields.description: For anyone who ever fantasized that She & Him is a real husband/wife duo, meet Tennis. The Denver pair's button-cute beach tunes (inspired by a seven month sailing sojourn) combine dreams of polo-clad love affairs at sea with the novel quality of reverb-drenched tunes you can actually hum along to. They're a throwback that works, thanks to Alaina Moore's sincere crooning and the band's doo-wop harmonies. The East Coast is the best coast, after all. With the fitting La Sera and Holiday Shores.
fields.title: Tennis

fields.description:
Electric Literature , the literary magazine founded in 2009 by Andy Hunter and Scott Lindenbaum, brings wonderful short stories not only to your bookstore, but to your iPhone, iPad, Kindle, and ebook as well. And now you can hear them on the stage as part of Symphony Space's "Selected Shorts" series. Comedian Mike Birbiglia ( Sleepwalk with Me ), John Lithgow, Aya Cash ( Traffic Light ), and David Rakoff perform new stories from the magazine by Rick Moody, Lydia Millet, and Joy Williams.

fields.description: After four studio albums full of erudite flourish, stately piano balladry, and pleasant nods to the '90s female singer-songwriter canon, Vienna Teng collaborated with vocalist and multi-instrumental whiz Alex Wong for the 2010 live recording  A Moment Always Vanishing . It was an apt title for a set where creative eddies often ran beautifully concurrent to the main action, and a surprise finale of a Radiohead cover acknowledged both artists' appreciation for the group's strength in ambiguity. Expect the duo to create the shifting  Vanishing  landscape on stage. With Justin Jones.

fields.description: As faithful  Us Weekly  readers already know, the Pretty Reckless is  Gossip Girl  star Taylor Momsen's sassed-out grunge-pop outfit. You can tell she's aiming for prime era Hole on  Light Me Up , the band's newly released debut, but more often than not, she ends up closer to Wolfmother. Good thing? Bad thing? Your call.
fields.title: The Pretty Reckless

fields.description: If you've yet to read  Sam Lipsyte 's  The Ask , we have just one question: What's the hold-up? One of the funniest books of 2010, the story concerns Milo Burke, a struggling father and husband who is given one last shot at keeping his job as a development officer at a university if he can woo a mysterious potential donor. The only catch is: The donor has a difficult favor to ask him as well.
